article.headline: Eastern Wash. 89, Portland State 70
article.story: PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Freshman Rodney Stuckey scored 31 points and Eastern Washington snapped a five-game losing streak with a 89-70 victory over Portland State Saturday night. Paul Butorac added 16 points and five rebounds and the Eagles (6-10, 1-2 Big Sky) led by as many as 22 points to spoil the Vikings' conference home opener. Josh Neeley had 15 points to lead Portland State (7-9, 0-3), which has lost three straight after a five-game winning streak. The Vikings had no answer for Stuckey, who had 15 points in the first half as the Eagles built a 49-32 lead, shooting 66.7 percent from the floor. Stuckey scored a school record 45 points in the Eagles' 105-95 loss to Northern Arizona last week. It was a record for a freshman in the Big Sky. Going into the game, he was averaging 22.7 points, tops among Division I freshmen. Stuckey's jumper put the Eagles up 22-7 in the first half, before a 3-pointer made it 31-17. The Eagles went up 59-40 on Stuckey's 3-pointer in the second half. Butorac's 3-pointer made it 74-55. Stuckey hit a seemingly impossible falling down jumper amid a crowd of defenders and added a free throw that made it 83-62 late in the game. Stuckey also had five assists and four steals for the Eagles, who finished 60.7 percent (34-for-56) from the floor. Portland State coach Ken Bone said Stuckey might be the best freshman the Big Sky has ever seen. "He's a great, great player. He's a great kid. I really like Rodney," Bone said. "I just wish he would have taken it easy on us." Jake Schroeder and Anthony Washington each had 14 points for the Vikings.
